  <!-- Overview -->
  <section class="mb-5">
    <h3 class="fw-semibold">Project Overview</h3>
    <p>
      This project analyzes more than a decade of reef fish monitoring data from the
      Twin Rocks Marine Sanctuary in Batangas, Philippines. The goal was to assess how
      long‑term protection influences fish abundance and biomass, using statistically
      rigorous and reproducible methods.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Why It Matters -->
  <section class="mb-5">
    <h3 class="fw-semibold">Why This Matters</h3>
    <p>
      Long‑term ecological datasets are rare and challenging to analyze due to observer
      effects, seasonality, and sampling variability. This work prioritizes methodological
      clarity and transparency, ensuring that observed trends can be meaningfully
      interpreted and withstand scientific scrutiny.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Data & Methods -->
  <section class="mb-5">
    <h3 class="fw-semibold">Data & Methodology</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Time span: 2009–2018</li>
      <li>Focus: target reef fish species ≥ 5 cm</li>
      <li>Sampling restricted to comparable months to reduce seasonality</li>
      <li>Statistical modeling and diagnostics performed in <strong>R</strong></li>
      <li>Emphasis on reproducibility and data validation</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Key Findings -->
  <section class="mb-5">
    <h3 class="fw-semibold">Key Findings</h3>
    <p>
      Results indicate significant differences in fish abundance between protected and
      comparison sites over time. While total fish counts varied, protected areas showed
      evidence of increased biomass driven by larger individual fish—highlighting how
      protection may shift ecosystem structure rather than simply increasing abundance.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Tools -->
  <section class="mb-5">
